====Noun====
{{en-noun|~|policies}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete}} The art of [[governance]]; [[political science]]. {{defdate|14th–18th c.}}
#* '''a. 1616''', {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''Henry V'', I.1:
#*: List his discourse of Warre; and you shall heare / A fearefull Battaile rendred you in Musique. / Turne him to any Cause of '''Pollicy''', / The Gordian Knot of it he will vnloose, / Familiar as his Garter {{...}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[state]]; a [[polity]]. {{defdate|14th–16th c.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A set political system; civil administration. {{defdate|15th–19th c.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[trick]]; a [[stratagem]]. {{defdate|15th–19th c.}}
#* '''a. 1594''', {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''Titus Andronicus'':
#*: 'Tis '''pollicie''', and stratageme must doe / That you affect, and so must you resolue, / That what you cannot as you would atcheiue, / You must perforce accomplish as you may.
# A [[principle]] of [[behaviour]], [[conduct]] etc. thought to be [[desirable]] or [[necessary]], especially as formally expressed by a [[government]] or other authoritative body. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#: ''The Communist Party has a '''policy''' of returning power to the workers.''
# [[wise|Wise]] or [[advantageous]] [[conduct]]; [[prudence]], formerly also with connotations of [[craftiness]]. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#* '''1813''', Jane Austen, ''Pride and Prejudice'', Modern Library Edition (1995), page 140:
#*: These bitter accusations might have been suppressed, had I with greater '''policy''' concealed my struggles, and flattered you {{...}}
#* Fuller
#*: The very '''policy''' of a hostess, finding his purse so far above his clothes, did detect him.
# {{lb|en|now|rare}} Specifically, political [[shrewdness]] or (formerly) [[cunning]]; [[statecraft]]. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#* '''1946''', {{w|Bertrand Russell}}, ''History of Western Philosophy'', I.25:
#*: Whether he believed himself a god, or only took on the attributes of divinity from motives of '''policy''', is a question for the psychologist, since the historical evidence is indecisive.
# {{lb|en|Scotland|now|chiefly|in the plural}} The [[grounds]] of a large country [[house]]. {{defdate|from 18th c.}}
#* '''1955''', {{w|Robin Jenkins}}, ''The Cone-Gatherers'', Canongate 2012, page 36:
#*: Next morning was so splendid that as he walked through the '''policies''' towards the mansion house despair itself was lulled.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Motive; object; inducement.
#* Sir Philip Sidney
#*: What '''policy''' have you to bestow a benefit where it is counted an injury?

